Key Challenges We’re Hearing About
1. Housing & Rent Burden – Skyrocketing rents and application requirements that often exclude tenants who cannot supply a Social Security number.
2. Employment & Workplace Abuse – Wage theft, misclassification, and retaliation when workers speak up about unsafe conditions.
3. Language Access & Digital Divide – Limited translation at public offices and a lack of affordable internet access hinder everything from school enrollment to tele-health.
4. Health & Mental Health Care – Lack of insurance, hesitation to seek care, and very few culturally responsive mental-health providers.
5. Legal Aid & Enforcement Anxiety – A shortage of low-cost immigration attorneys and fear of enforcement actions keep some families from reporting crimes or attending court.

Recent Local Policies & Initiatives
• Language Access Ordinance 22-45 (passed March 2024) – Requires city agencies to offer vital documents and interpretation in the top ten languages.
• Municipal ID Pilot (launching July 2024) – Will allow residents to open bank accounts, enter schools, and interact with police without a state-issued ID.
• End of State Emergency Rental Assistance (January 2024) – Rent debt is rising now that this program has sunset, leaving many households one paycheck away from eviction.
• Nourish Neighbors Food Initiative – A volunteer-run pantry that served 50+ families last month while also connecting them with other resources.
• Monthly Pro-Bono Immigration Clinics – Run in partnership with the County Legal Aid Society; average wait-list is six weeks.

